  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Balkan Floods 2014</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Between 14 and 18 May 2014 a low-pressure cyclone designated Tamara (also Yvette ) affected a large area of Southeastern and Central Europe causing floods and landslides. Serbia and Bosnia and Herzegovina suffered the greatest damage as the rain was the heaviest in 120 years of recorded weather measurements. By 20 May at least 62 people had died as a result of the flooding and hundreds of thousands had been forced from their homes. Floodwaters caused over 2 000 landslides across the Balkan region spreading damage across many towns and villages. The rains activated torrents and mudslides and subsequently several rivers in watersheds of Sava and Morava rose and flooded surrounding valleys. Official counts indicate that over 1.6 million people were affected in Serbia and Bosnia after a week of flooding. BRC launched a public appeal raising a total of 223 361 (net) by the time it closed on 13 October 2014. BRC has supported with the deployment of delegates and a cash pledge of 187 019 to the IFRC EA in October earmarked towards Phase 2 of the Cash Transfer Programme in Bosnia and Herzegovina.</narrative>
  </description>
